stitute of Living in 1943; incorporated into Hartford Hospital 1994. Now a comprehensive psychiatric facility at 200 Retreat Avenue, Hartford. Connecticut History Online article covers history in detail. [Apr 2026 cleanup — merged from duplicate INST108]: Chartered by Connecticut General Assembly 1822 following petition from the Connecticut State Medical Society; opened April 4, 1824. The only mental asylum in the United States founded by a state medical society. Eli Todd took up the cause after his sister's depression and suicide. Sources: APA Foundation; Goodheart 'Mad Yankees' (UMass Press, 2003); Braceland 'Institute of Living: The Hartford Retreat 1822-1972'; Connecticut History (CTHumanities).\n[former/alt detail] Now the Institute of Living (Hartford Hospital campus)"},"INST022":{"id":"INST022","primary_name":"American Board of Commissioners for Foreign Missions","name":"American Board of Commissioners for Foreign Missions","alt_names":["ABCFM","American Board"],"type":"missionary_society","founding_year":1810,"location":{"city":"Boston","state":"Massachusetts"},"primary_persons":["X00724"],"hooker_connected_people":["X00724","X02121","X02122","T01213","H00527","I01195"],"person_ids":[],"related_institutions":[],"related_landmarks":[],"tags":["native_american_contact","missionary"],"sources":[{"short":"Wikipedia","note":"Elias Cornelius (clergyman); ABCFM"}],"notes":"First American foreign-mission organization. Tree connections: Rev. Elias Cornelius (agent 1816, secretary 1831-32); Ainsworth and Harriet Ellsworth Blunt, missionaries to the Cherokee at Brainerd, Tennessee; Eliza Talcott, missionary to Japan; Rev. William Banfield Capron, Madura mission; Judge John Hooker, member."}},"crossConnections":[{"type":"artifact","related_id":"HD0411","link_text":"Rev. Thomas Hopkins Gallaudet","display_label":"co-wrote his schoolbooks and founded America's deaf school","slug":"thomas-gallaudet-1787"}]}